[## [SECTION: Step 1 — Extend VectorStore with ingest() and stats()]]

10
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:30,000
Before we build the query engine, we need to extend our VectorStore.
The API routes will call store.ingest and store.stats.

11
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:36,000
Open src/financial_rag/storage/vector_store.py.
We already have the VectorStore class. Now we add two methods.

12
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:42,000
First, the ingest method.
This is the full pipeline for ingesting a single filing.

13
01:40:42,000 --> 01:40:48,000
It takes three parameters.
chunks from the text processor, filing metadata, and the file hash.

14
01:40:48,000 --> 01:40:54,000
It returns a tuple of filing ID and the number of chunks stored.
Let me walk through each step.

15
01:40:54,000 --> 01:41:00,000
Step one. deduplication check.
We create a database session and instantiate FilingsRepository.

16
01:41:00,000 --> 01:41:06,000
We check if a filing with this hash already exists.
If yes, we raise DuplicateFilingError.

17
01:41:06,000 --> 01:41:12,000
This prevents ingesting the same filing twice.
The ingestion pipeline must be idempotent.

18
01:41:12,000 --> 01:41:18,000
Step two. embed all chunks.
We call embed_chunks on the embedding client.

19
01:41:18,000 --> 01:41:24,000
This method takes a list of FinancialChunk objects.
It populates the embedding field on each one.

20
01:41:24,000 --> 01:41:30,000
The embedding client handles batching automatically.
It also tracks token usage and cost.

21
01:41:30,000 --> 01:41:36,000
Step three. register the filing.
We generate a new UUID for the filing ID.

22
01:41:36,000 --> 01:41:42,000
We create a Filing ORM instance with all the metadata.
Ticker, filing type, fiscal year, source URL, and file hash.

23
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:48,000
We set ingested_by to VectorStore and is_active to True.
Then we add it to the database using FilingsRepository.

24
01:41:48,000 --> 01:41:54,000
Step four. bulk upsert the chunks.
First, we set the filing_id on all chunks.

25
01:41:54,000 --> 01:42:00,000
They had placeholder UUIDs from the text processor.
Now we attach them to the correct filing.

26
01:42:00,000 --> 01:42:06,000
Then we call bulk_upsert on ChunksRepository.
This inserts or updates all chunks in a single operation.

27
01:42:06,000 --> 01:42:12,000
We log the completion with filing ID and chunk count.
Then return both to the caller.

28
01:42:12,000 --> 01:42:18,000
Now the stats method.
This returns storage statistics for monitoring.

29
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:24,000
The stats method takes an optional ticker parameter.
If provided, it returns counts for just that company.

30
01:42:24,000 --> 01:42:30,000
We create a database session and instantiate both repositories.
ChunksRepository and FilingsRepository.

31
01:42:30,000 --> 01:42:36,000
If a ticker is provided, we use count_by_ticker and get_by_ticker.
If not, we use the global count methods.

32
01:42:36,000 --> 01:42:42,000
The result is a dictionary with ticker, total chunks,
total filings, embedding provider, and dimensions.

33
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:48,000
This is useful for monitoring your ingestion progress.
And for debugging configuration issues.

34
01:42:48,000 --> 01:42:54,000
With both methods added, the VectorStore is now complete.
The API routes can call ingest for new filings and stats for dashboards.


[## [SECTION: Step 2 — Extend DatabaseClient with health_check() and verify_pgvector()]]

35
01:42:54,000 --> 01:43:00,000
Now let's extend our DatabaseClient with two methods.
Health check and verify pgvector.

36
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:06,000
These are called by the API routes and startup dependencies.
They give us visibility into database health.

37
01:43:06,000 --> 01:43:12,000
Open src/financial_rag/storage/database.py.
We already have the DatabaseClient class.

38
01:43:12,000 --> 01:43:18,000
First, let's add the health_check method.
This runs a lightweight liveness probe against PostgreSQL.

39
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:24,000
If the engine is None, meaning the client isn't initialised,
we return a disconnected status.

40
01:43:24,000 --> 01:43:30,000
If connected, we open a connection and run a query.
We select the PostgreSQL version and the server start time.

41
01:43:30,000 --> 01:43:36,000
We also get pool statistics from the engine's pool.
Pool size, checked out connections, and overflow.

42
01:43:36,000 --> 01:43:42,000
The result is a dictionary with status, PostgreSQL version,
server start time, and pool statistics.

43
01:43:42,000 --> 01:43:48,000
If any exception occurs, we log the error.
And we raise DatabaseConnectionError with the details.

44
01:43:48,000 --> 01:43:54,000
Now let's add verify_pgvector.
This checks that the pgvector extension is installed and accessible.

45
01:43:54,000 --> 01:44:00,000
We query the pg_extension table.
We look for the extension named vector.

46
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:06,000
If the scalar result is not None, the extension exists.
We log success and return True.

47
01:44:06,000 --> 01:44:12,000
If not, we log an error with instructions.
Run CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector.

48
01:44:12,000 --> 01:44:18,000
We call this method at application startup.
Before any embedding operations begin.

49
01:44:18,000 --> 01:44:24,000
If pgvector is missing, we can fail fast.
Better to know at startup than when the first query fails.

50
01:44:24,000 --> 01:44:30,000
Our database client now has health checks.
The system can now self-monitor.


[## [SECTION: Step 3 — Extend CacheClient with health_check()]]

51
01:44:30,000 --> 01:44:36,000
Now let's extend CacheClient with health_check.
Open src/financial_rag/storage/cache.py.

52
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:42,000
The health_check method for Redis is similar to the database version.
If Redis is None, return disconnected status.

53
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:48,000
If connected, we ping Redis to verify it's responding.
Then we fetch server info using the info command.

54
01:44:48,000 --> 01:44:54,000
We extract Redis version, memory usage, and connected clients.
We also include pool statistics if available.

55
01:44:54,000 --> 01:45:00,000
If a RedisError occurs, we log it.
And we raise CacheConnectionError.

56
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:06,000
These health check methods are critical for production.
They let your monitoring system know if a service is down.

57
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:12,000
A typical health endpoint would call both.
If either fails, the API returns 503 Service Unavailable.

58
01:45:12,000 --> 01:45:18,000
Our database and cache clients now have health checks.
The system can now self-monitor.


[## [SECTION: Step 4 — Query Engine (Components #29, #38)]]

59
01:45:18,000 --> 01:45:24,000
Now let's build the query engine.
This is the public interface for the entire retrieval layer.

60
01:45:24,000 --> 01:45:30,000
Everything above this, like API routes and agents,
talks only to QueryEngine. Never directly to DocumentRetriever or HybridSearcher.

61
01:45:30,000 --> 01:45:36,000
The QueryEngine orchestrates the full RAG pipeline.
Retrieve relevant chunks, assemble context, call the LLM, and return the result.

62
01:45:36,000 --> 01:45:42,000
First, imports. We need logging, time, and dataclasses.
From typing, we import Literal for type hints.

63
01:45:42,000 --> 01:45:48,000
From openai, we import AsyncOpenAI.
From our application, we import get_settings.

64
01:45:48,000 --> 01:45:54,000
From retrieval, we import DocumentRetriever, RetrievalResult, and HybridSearcher.
From storage, we import VectorStore.
And from utils, we import RetrievalError.

65
01:45:54,000 --> 01:46:00,000
Now define the system prompts for each analysis style.
Three styles. analyst, executive, and risk.

66
01:46:00,000 --> 01:46:06,000
The analyst prompt asks for detailed, precise analysis.
Cite specific figures, dates, and sections.

67
01:46:06,000 --> 01:46:12,000
The executive prompt is for CFO-level advisors.
Concise, decision-ready, lead with the most important finding.

68
01:46:12,000 --> 01:46:18,000
The risk prompt is for a chief risk officer.
Analyse for financial risks, regulatory exposures, and operational vulnerabilities.

69
01:46:18,000 --> 01:46:24,000
Now define the QueryResult dataclass.
This is the complete result from a RAG query.

70
01:46:24,000 --> 01:46:30,000
It contains the question, answer, analysis style, search type,
latency in milliseconds, source documents, and any error.

71
01:46:30,000 --> 01:46:36,000
The latency_seconds property converts milliseconds to seconds.
And the repr method gives us readable debug output.

72
01:46:36,000 --> 01:46:42,000
Now the QueryEngine class.
In __init__, we load settings and create the vector store.

73
01:46:42,000 --> 01:46:48,000
We instantiate DocumentRetriever and HybridSearcher.
And we build the LLM client.

74
01:46:48,000 --> 01:46:54,000
The _build_llm_client method is our circuit breaker.
If MOCK_EXTERNAL_APIS is True, we return None.

75
01:46:54,000 --> 01:47:00,000
If OPENAI_API_KEY is not set, we log a warning and return None.
The query method will return raw context instead of crashing.

76
01:47:00,000 --> 01:47:06,000
This is the simplest possible circuit breaker.
Never let the LLM being down take down the entire service.

77
01:47:06,000 --> 01:47:12,000
Now the main query method.
This runs the full RAG pipeline for a question.

78
01:47:12,000 --> 01:47:18,000
We record the start time with time.monotonic.
This gives us high-precision latency measurement.

79
01:47:18,000 --> 01:47:24,000
If the analysis style is invalid, we fall back to analyst.
Then we call _retrieve to get relevant chunks.

80
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:30,000
Here's an important feature. auto-upgrade.
If we used similarity search and the top result's score is below the threshold.

81
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:36,000
We automatically upgrade to hybrid search.
This gives better results for queries that need exact term matching.

82
01:47:36,000 --> 01:47:42,000
If no results are found at all, we return a friendly message.
I could not find relevant information in the available financial documents.

83
01:47:42,000 --> 01:47:48,000
If we have results, we build the context using build_context.
This respects the token budget.

84
01:47:48,000 --> 01:47:54,000
Then we call _generate_answer with the question, context, and style.
The LLM produces a grounded answer.

85
01:47:54,000 --> 01:48:00,000
We calculate the total latency and log the result.
Then we return a QueryResult with all the information.

86
01:48:00,000 --> 01:48:06,000
If any exception occurs during the query, we catch it.
We log the error and return a QueryResult with the error field set.

87
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:12,000
The API never crashes. It always returns a valid response.
This is the graceful degradation principle.

88
01:48:12,000 --> 01:48:18,000
The _retrieve method routes to the appropriate retrieval strategy.
If search_type is hybrid, we call HybridSearcher.

89
01:48:18,000 --> 01:48:24,000
Otherwise we call DocumentRetriever with the requested search_type.
Similarity or MMR.

90
01:48:24,000 --> 01:48:30,000
The _generate_answer method calls the LLM.
We format the system prompt and user message.

91
01:48:30,000 --> 01:48:36,000
If the LLM client is None, we return the raw context.
This is the circuit breaker in action.

92
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:42,000
Let me explain the routing table one more time.

93
01:48:42,000 --> 01:48:48,000
Search type similarity goes to DocumentRetriever with pgvector.
Search type MMR also goes to DocumentRetriever but with diversity ranking.

94
01:48:48,000 --> 01:48:54,000
Search type hybrid goes to HybridSearcher.
Vector plus full-text with RRF fusion.

95
01:48:54,000 --> 01:49:00,000
And if similarity scores are below the threshold, we auto-upgrade to hybrid.
This gives you the best of both worlds automatically.

96
01:49:00,000 --> 01:49:06,000
Let me also explain the LLM_BASE_URL configuration.

97
01:49:06,000 --> 01:49:12,000
Your .env defaults set LLM_BASE_URL to Groq's endpoint.
But LLM_PROVIDER is still OpenAI.

98
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:18,000
This is intentional. Groq exposes an OpenAI-compatible API.
You can use the OpenAI SDK with Groq's faster inference.

99
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:24,000
In development, this saves money significantly.
For production with GPT-4o, simply remove LLM_BASE_URL from .env.

100
01:49:24,000 --> 01:49:30,000
Our query engine is complete.
Now the API routes can use it to answer questions.

133
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:48,000
We import QueryEngine and QueryResult from QueryEngine.
Then we add them to __all__.

134
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:54,000
Our QueryEngine repository is complete.


[## [SECTION: Step 5 — Analysis History Repository (Components #36–37)]]

101
01:49:30,000 --> 01:49:36,000
Now let's build the analysis history repository.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/analysis.py

102
01:49:36,000 --> 01:49:42,000
This is the audit trail for every query that goes through the system.
All analysis records are stored here permanently.

103
01:49:42,000 --> 01:49:48,000
The table is append-only by design. No updates, no deletions.
Every query gets a permanent record.

104
01:49:48,000 --> 01:49:54,000
Why append-only? Financial analysis systems need tamper-evident audit logs.
If a user later disputes an answer, you can show exactly what was asked.

105
01:49:54,000 --> 01:50:00,000
You can see what documents were retrieved, what the model said, and the timestamp.
This is also essential for debugging model drift over time.

106
01:50:00,000 --> 01:50:06,000
First, imports. We need logging, datetime with UTC, typing, and UUID.

107
01:50:06,000 --> 01:50:12,000
From SQLAlchemy, we import Boolean, Integer, String, Text, func, and select.
From postgresql dialects, we import ARRAY and UUID types.

108
01:50:12,000 --> 01:50:18,000
From our application, we import Base, BaseRepository, and DatabaseQueryError.

109
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:24,000
Now define the AnalysisRecord ORM model.
This maps to the analysis_history table we created in Phase one.

110
01:50:24,000 --> 01:50:30,000
We have id as primary key, ticker, question, and answer.
Analysis style, agent type, search type, and latency in milliseconds.

111
01:50:30,000 --> 01:50:36,000
Notice latency_ms is stored as integer, not float.
This is for efficient range queries and aggregations.

112
01:50:36,000 --> 01:50:42,000
AVG latency on an integer column is faster than on a float.
Convert to seconds only at the presentation layer.

113
01:50:42,000 --> 01:50:48,000
We have source_chunk_ids as a PostgreSQL array of UUIDs.
This stores which chunks were used to generate the answer.

114
01:50:48,000 --> 01:50:54,000
Real_time_used is a boolean for live market data.
Error field captures any failures.

115
01:50:54,000 --> 01:51:00,000
Session_id groups multiple queries from the same conversation.
And created_at is automatically set to the current UTC time.

116
01:51:00,000 --> 01:51:06,000
Now the AnalysisRepository class.
It inherits from BaseRepository with AnalysisRecord as the model.

117
01:51:06,000 --> 01:51:12,000
The record method is the primary write method.
It appends a completed analysis to the history table.

118
01:51:12,000 --> 01:51:18,000
We generate a new UUID for the record.
We convert ticker to uppercase if provided.

119
01:51:18,000 --> 01:51:24,000
We store the question, answer, analysis style, agent type, and search type.
Latency is stored as milliseconds.

120
01:51:24,000 --> 01:51:30,000
Source chunk IDs default to an empty list.
Error and session_id are optional.

121
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:36,000
Then we call the base repository's add method.
This persists the record to the database.

122
01:51:36,000 --> 01:51:42,000
Now the read methods.
get_by_ticker returns analysis history for a ticker, newest first.

123
01:51:42,000 --> 01:51:48,000
We order by created_at descending and apply limit and offset for pagination.

124
01:51:48,000 --> 01:51:54,000
get_by_session returns all records belonging to a session.
In chronological order, not newest first, because conversation order matters.

125
01:51:54,000 --> 01:52:00,000
get_recent returns the most recent analyses globally.
Useful for monitoring dashboards and debugging.

126
01:52:00,000 --> 01:52:06,000
We can filter by agent type or only show errors.
This helps identify which agents are having problems.

127
01:52:06,000 --> 01:52:12,000
Now aggregation methods for monitoring.
average_latency_ms returns the average query latency.

128
01:52:12,000 --> 01:52:18,000
We can filter by ticker or agent type.
This helps track performance per company or per agent.

129
01:52:18,000 --> 01:52:24,000
error_rate returns the fraction of analyses that resulted in an error.
Returns 0.0 if no records exist.

130
01:52:24,000 --> 01:52:30,000
We calculate total records and error records separately.
Then divide errors by total.

131
01:52:30,000 --> 01:52:36,000
These aggregations are critical for production monitoring.
You can alert if error rate spikes above a threshold.

132
01:52:36,000 --> 01:52:42,000
Now let's update the repositories __init__.py to export AnalysisRepository.
Open src/financial_rag/storage/repositories/__init__.py.

133
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:48,000
We import AnalysisRecord and AnalysisRepository from analysis.
Then we add them to __all__.

134
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:54,000
Our analysis repository is complete.
The audit trail is now ready to record every query.


[## [SECTION: Step 6 — Financial Agent (Components #30–35)]]

135
01:52:54,000 --> 01:53:00,000
Now let's build the financial agent.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/agents/financial_agent.py

136
01:53:00,000 --> 01:53:06,000
This is the intelligent reasoning layer.
It adds multi-step search orchestration on top of the query engine.

137
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:12,000
Instead of a single retrieval call, the agent can decide what to search for.
And it can search multiple times before synthesizing an answer.

138
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:18,000
First, imports. We need json, logging, time, and dataclasses.
From typing, we import Any and Literal.

139
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:24,000
From openai, we import AsyncOpenAI.
From our application, we import get_settings.

140
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:30,000
From retrieval, we import RetrievalResult and QueryEngine.
From storage, we import VectorStore.

141
01:53:30,000 --> 01:53:36,000
Now define the AgentResult dataclass.
This is richer than QueryResult because it includes the tool call trace.

142
01:53:36,000 --> 01:53:42,000
It contains the question, answer, analysis style, latency,
source documents, tool calls, reasoning steps, and any error.

143
01:53:42,000 --> 01:53:48,000
The to_query_result method converts to QueryResult for API compatibility.
This lets you use the agent anywhere you'd use the query engine.

144
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:54,000
Now the system prompts for each analysis style.
Analyst, executive, and risk.

145
01:53:54,000 --> 01:54:00,000
The analyst prompt asks for detailed, evidence-based answers.
Cite specific figures, dates, and document sections.

146
01:54:00,000 --> 01:54:06,000
The executive prompt is for CFO-level advisors.
Lead with the most important finding, be direct and quantitative.

147
01:54:06,000 --> 01:54:12,000
The risk prompt focuses on risk factors and legal proceedings.
Quantify risks where possible and flag exposures explicitly.

148
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:18,000
Now define the tools for OpenAI function calling.
First tool. search_filings.

149
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:24,000
It takes a query string, optional ticker, optional section, and optional fiscal year.
The model uses this to retrieve relevant passages from SEC filings.

150
01:54:24,000 --> 01:54:30,000
Second tool. compare_filings.
Use this when the question asks about trends or year-over-year changes.

151
01:54:30,000 --> 01:54:36,000
It takes a query, a ticker, and an optional list of years.
The model calls this to compare data across multiple fiscal periods.

152
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:42,000
Now the FinancialAgent class.
In __init__, we load settings and create the query engine.

153
01:54:42,000 --> 01:54:48,000
We also build the LLM client. If OpenAI is unavailable,
the agent falls back to direct query engine.

154
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:54,000
The analyze method is the main public API.
It takes a question, optional ticker and fiscal year, analysis style, and max tool calls.

155
01:54:54,000 --> 01:55:00,000
First, we check if the LLM is available.
If not, we fall back to QueryEngine immediately.

156
01:55:00,000 --> 01:55:06,000
If LLM is available, we run the agent loop.
This is where the magic happens.

157
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:12,000
Let me explain the agent loop in plain English.

158
01:55:12,000 --> 01:55:18,000
Step one. Send the question to the LLM with tool definitions attached.
The model sees what tools are available.

159
01:55:18,000 --> 01:55:24,000
Step two. The LLM decides what to search for.
It returns structured JSON describing which tool to call and with what arguments.

160
01:55:24,000 --> 01:55:30,000
Step three. Your code executes the tool call.
We call search_filings or compare_filings against our database.

161
01:55:30,000 --> 01:55:36,000
Step four. The tool result goes back into the conversation.
The LLM sees what was retrieved.

162
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:42,000
Step five. Loop. The LLM may call more tools, or produce a final answer.
Continue until the model stops requesting tool calls.

163
01:55:42,000 --> 01:55:48,000
Notice the max_tool_calls safety cap.
Without this, a misbehaving model could loop indefinitely.

164
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:54,000
The cap defaults to five. Enough for complex multi-year comparisons.
But prevents runaway API costs.

165
01:55:54,000 --> 01:56:00,000
When the cap is hit, we call the LLM one final time without the tools parameter.
This forces it to answer from whatever context it has accumulated.

166
01:56:00,000 --> 01:56:06,000
Now the tool execution methods.
_execute_tool routes to the appropriate tool handler.

167
01:56:06,000 --> 01:56:12,000
_tool_search_filings calls the query engine with the provided parameters.
It returns a formatted context string and the retrieved chunks.

168
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:18,000
_tool_compare_filings runs multiple searches across different years.
It caps at three years to keep responses reasonable.

169
01:56:18,000 --> 01:56:24,000
It returns a combined context string with year-by-year breakdowns.
And all source chunks for the audit trail.

170
01:56:24,000 --> 01:56:30,000
Let me highlight the fallback layers.
If the LLM client can't be built, we fall back to QueryEngine.

171
01:56:30,000 --> 01:56:36,000
If the agent loop hits an exception, we also fall back.
The API never crashes. It always returns a response.

172
01:56:36,000 --> 01:56:42,000
This is the graceful degradation principle.
Better to return a slightly less intelligent answer than no answer at all.

173
01:56:42,000 --> 01:56:48,000
Now let's create the agents package __init__.py.
Open src/financial_rag/agents/__init__.py.

174
01:56:48,000 --> 01:56:54,000
We import AgentResult and FinancialAgent from financial_agent.
Then we expose both in __all__.

175
01:56:54,000 --> 01:57:00,000
Now anywhere in the application, you can import.
from financial_rag.agents import FinancialAgent

176
01:57:00,000 --> 01:57:06,000
Our financial agent is complete.
Now the API can offer intelligent, multi-step reasoning to users.


[## [SECTION: Step 7 — Phase 4 Verification Test]]

177
01:57:06,000 --> 01:57:12,000
Now let's write integration tests for Phase 4.
We'll put them in tests/integration/test_phase4_agent.py

178
01:57:12,000 --> 01:57:18,000
These tests verify the query engine, agent, and analysis repository.
Unit tests run without an LLM API key using mock mode.

179
01:57:18,000 --> 01:57:24,000
Integration tests require a live LLM API key.
They are marked with the integration pytest marker.

180
01:57:24,000 --> 01:57:30,000
First, TestQueryResult.
This verifies the QueryResult value object works correctly.

181
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:36,000
The first test checks that latency_seconds converts correctly.
1500 milliseconds should become 1.5 seconds.

182
01:57:36,000 --> 01:57:42,000
The second test checks that repr includes key fields.
Analysis style and latency should appear in the string representation.

183
01:57:42,000 --> 01:57:48,000
Now TestAgentResult.
This verifies the AgentResult value object.

184
01:57:48,000 --> 01:57:54,000
The first test checks to_query_result conversion.
It ensures an AgentResult can become a QueryResult for API compatibility.

185
01:57:54,000 --> 01:58:00,000
The second test checks that latency_seconds works correctly.
2000 milliseconds should become 2.0 seconds.

186
01:58:00,000 --> 01:58:06,000
Now TestAnalysisRepository.
These are integration tests that require a real database.

187
01:58:06,000 --> 01:58:12,000
The record test creates a new analysis record.
It verifies that an ID was generated and the fields match.

188
01:58:12,000 --> 01:58:18,000
The get_by_ticker test retrieves records for a specific company.
It should always return a list, even if empty.

189
01:58:18,000 --> 01:58:24,000
The average_latency test inserts a record and computes the average.
It verifies the aggregation method works.

190
01:58:24,000 --> 01:58:30,000
The error_rate test checks that a non-existent ticker returns zero.
No records means zero percent error rate.

191
01:58:30,000 --> 01:58:36,000
Now TestQueryEngineMocked.
These tests run without an LLM API key using mock mode.

192
01:58:36,000 --> 01:58:42,000
We monkeypatch MOCK_EXTERNAL_APIS to true.
Then we clear the settings cache so the change takes effect.

193
01:58:42,000 --> 01:58:48,000
The first test verifies the query engine returns a QueryResult.
Even without an LLM, the engine returns the question and context.

194
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:54,000
The second test verifies the agent falls back to query engine.
When the LLM is unavailable, agent_type becomes query_engine_fallback.

195
01:58:54,000 --> 01:59:00,000
Finally, the db fixture.
This creates a real database client and connects.

196
01:59:00,000 --> 01:59:06,000
It yields the client to the test, then disconnects afterward.
This ensures each test gets a fresh database connection.

197
01:59:06,000 --> 01:59:12,000
Now let's talk about how to run these tests.

198
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:18,000
To run only the unit tests that don't need a database,
use pytest with the minus k flag to exclude integration.

199
01:59:18,000 --> 01:59:24,000
These tests are fast and don't require any external services.

200
01:59:24,000 --> 01:59:30,000
To run the integration tests that require a live database and LLM API key,
use pytest with the minus m integration flag.

201
01:59:30,000 --> 01:59:36,000
These tests will incur API costs if you have an LLM key set.
Run them sparingly during development.

202
01:59:36,000 --> 01:59:42,000
Our Phase four integration tests are complete.
The query engine, agent, and analysis repository are verified.

